  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970\n- Requires financial institutions to report certain transactions\n- Mandates reporting of cash transactions over $10,000\n- Helps prevent money laundering\n\n2. The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Makes money laundering a federal criminal offense\n- Establishes penalties for individuals and institutions involved in money laundering\n\n3. The USA PATRIOT Act of 2001\n- Expanded anti-money laundering provisions\n- Enhanced reporting and monitoring requirements\n- Increased penalties for money laundering activities\n\n4. The Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- Updated and modernized existing money laundering laws\n- Increased corporate transparency requirements\n- Expanded regulatory oversight\n\nAt the federal level, money laundering is primarily prosecuted under 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 and \u00a7 1957, which define different types of money laundering offenses and establish criminal penalties.\n\nState laws also exist to address money laundering, often mirroring federal statutes but with variations in specific provisions and penalties.\n\nThese statutes collectively aim to detect, prevent, and prosecute financial crimes involving illegal monetary transactions.",
